    <div class="artwork__inner">
              <dl class="specification-list">
        <dt>Gallery Text</dt>
        <dd>
        <dl>
        <dt> </dt>
        <dl><p>This figure was found behind the altar of the church of Santa Maria de Taüll in Catalonia, Spain, in 1907; the original context and subject of the sculpture remain unknown. It may have been part of a sculptural group representing the Three Marys, pious women said to have been present at the crucifixion of Jesus. Traces of paint on the sculpture indicate that it was once brightly colored. Its large headdress is typical of 12th- century Catalonian art, particularly as seen in wall paintings found at the nearby church of Sant Climent. This region, in the northeast of Spain, was rich in religious orders that supported the visual arts. The sculpture was once owned by Alphonse Kann, a great early 20th-century French collector of medieval objects. </p></dl>
</dt></dl></dd></dl>


<dl class="specification-list">

